<section xml:id="section-completing-the-square">

<!-- TODO: Change title? -->
    <title>Completing the Square</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>In this section, we will learn how to complete the square. This method is very useful for solving quadratic equations and putting quadratic functions in vertex form.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="3LB4fUyyCL8" />
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Exploring Quadratic Functions with Graphing Technology</title>
        <!-- Include vertex, axis of symmetry, intercepts, domain and range  -->

        <p>In real life, engineers use technology to solve math application problems. Let's explore quadratic functions with graphing technology.</p>

        <example>
            <!-- Question f is solving graphically -->
            <statement>
                <p>A missile was detected flying toward a target. It's height, in meters, can be modeled by the quadratic equation <m>h(t)=-0.8t^2+132t+2718.2</m>, where <m>t</m> is the number of seconds since the missile was detected. Use graphing technology to answer the following questions. Make sure to use function notation when needed.
                <ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>When the missile was detected, how high was it flying?</p></li>
                    <li><p>Use a table to list the missile's height within the first <m>10</m> seconds since it was detected.</p></li>
                    <li><p>What was the missile's height <m>60</m> seconds since it was detected?</p></li>
                    <li><p>What's the maximum height the missile will reach?</p></li>
                    <li><p>After how many seconds will the missile hit its target on the ground?</p></li>
                    <li><p>When was the missile <m>8,000</m> meters high?</p></li>
                    <li><p>By the time the missile hit its target, how long has it traveled since being launched?</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>With graphing technology, and after adjusting the window settings, we can see the graph of the function <m>h(t)=-0.8t^2+132t+2718.2</m> and some critical points.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>h(t)=-0.8t^2+132t+2718.2</m></caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-2000,ymax=12000,xmin=-50,xmax=250,
                                        xtick={empty},ytick={empty},
                                        minor ytick={2000,4000,...,10000},
                                        minor xtick={50,100,150,200},
                                        xlabel={time in seconds},ylabel={height in meters}]
                                \addplot [<->, red, domain=-30:195] {-0.8*x^2+132*x+2718.2} node[pos=0.70,right] {$h(t)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, blue] coordinates {(82.5,8163.2)} node[above, blue] {\scriptsize $(82.5,8163.2)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, blue] coordinates {(60,7758.2)} node[below, blue] {\scriptsize $(60,7758.2)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, blue] coordinates {(183.515,0)} node[below left, blue] {\scriptsize $(183.515,0)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, blue] coordinates {(-18.515,0)} node[below right, blue] {\scriptsize $(-18.515,0)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, blue] coordinates {(0,2718.2)} node[right, blue] {\scriptsize $(0,2718.2)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Now we can answer questions based on information in the graph.
                    <ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>When the missile was detected, how high was it flying?</p>
                        <p>Since <m>t</m> represents the number of seconds since the missile was detected, it was detected at <m>t=0</m> seconds. The <m>y</m>-intercept in the graph is <m>(0,2718.2)</m>, so the missile was <m>2718.2</m> meters high at that moment.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Use a table to list the missile's height within the first <m>10</m> seconds since it was detected.</p>
                        <p>Graphing technology can show a table of values for the function. Once we change the starting value to <m>0</m> and the step increase to <m>1</m>, we should see the following table of values:</p>
                        <table>
                            <tabular>
                                <row bottom="medium">
                                    <cell><m>t</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>h(t)</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>2718.2</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>2849.4</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>2979</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3107</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3233.4</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3358.2</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3481.4</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3603</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3723</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>9</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3841.4</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>10</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>3958.2</m></cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>
                        </table>
                    </li>    
                    <li><p>What was the missile's height <m>60</m> seconds after it was detected?</p>
                        <p>In the function <m>h(t)=-0.8t^2+132t+2718.2</m>, <m>t</m> stands for time in seconds after the missile was detected. We substitute <m>t=60</m> into the function, and the graphing calculator shows the point <m>(60,7758.2)</m>, which implies the missile was <m>7758.2</m> meters high <m>60</m> seconds since it was detected.</p></li>
                    <li><p>What's the maximum height the missile will reach?</p>
                        <p>The parabola's vertex is at <m>(82.5,8163.2)</m>. This implies, <m>82.5</m> seconds since the missile was detected, it would reach its maximum height of <m>8163.2</m> meters.</p></li>
                    <li><p>After how many seconds will the missile hit its target on the ground?</p>
                        <p>The parabola's right-side <m>x</m>-intercept is at <m>(183.515,0)</m>. This implies the missile will fall back to the ground (hitting its target) <m>183.515</m> seconds since it was detected.</p></li>
                    <li><p>When was the missile <m>8,000</m> meters high?</p>
                        <p>To find when the missile was <m>8,000</m> meters high, we are asking: "What was <m>t</m>'s value when <m>h(t)=8000</m>?" We need to graph an additional horizontal line to find this information:</p>

                        <figure>
                            <caption>Graph of <m>h(t)=-0.8t^2+132t+2718.2</m> with <m>y=8000</m></caption>
                            <image width="60%">
                                <description></description>
                                <latex-image-code>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-2000,ymax=12000,xmin=-50,xmax=250,
                                                xtick={empty},ytick={empty},
