                                                minor xtick={50,100,150,200},
                                                xlabel={time in seconds},ylabel={height in meters}]
                                        \addplot [<->, red, domain=-30:195, samples=200] {-0.8*x^2+132*x+2718.2} node[pos=0.70,right] {$h(t)$};
                                        \addplot [<->, red, domain=-50:250] {8000} node[pos=0.80,below] {$y=8000$};
                                        \addplot [soliddot, blue] coordinates {(96.78,8000)} node[above right, blue] {\scriptsize $(96.78,8000)$};
                                        \addplot [soliddot, blue] coordinates {(68.22,8000)} node[above left, blue] {\scriptsize $(68.22,8000)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                                </latex-image-code>
                            </image>
                        </figure>

                        <p>According to the graph, the missile was <m>8000</m> meters high twice during its flight: <m>68.22</m> seconds and <m>96.78</m> seconds since it was detected.</p></li>
                    <li><p>By the time the missile hit its target, how long has it traveled since being launched?</p>
                        <p>The right-side <m>x</m>-intercept, <m>(183.515,0)</m>, represents the point when the missile hit its target; while the left-side <m>x</m>-intercept, <m>(-18.515,0)</m>, represents the point when the missile was launched. The difference between their <m>x</m>-values is the time of the missile's complete flight. So the missile traveled a total of <m>183.515-(-18.515)=202.3</m> seconds.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Quadratic Equations and Inequalities Graphically</title>
        
        <p>Now that we have seen how to find points on a parabola using graphing technology, we can solve quadratic equations graphically. Let's look at an example.</p>

        <example>
                <p>A reduced-gravity aircraft is a fixed-wing airplane that astronauts use for training. The airplane flies up and then down in a parabolic path to simulate the feeling of weightlessness. In one training flight, the pilot will fly about 40-60 parabolic maneuvers. (You can read more on <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reduced-gravity_aircraft">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reduced-gravity<underscore/>aircraft</url>.)</p>

                <p>The height of the training plane, in feet, at time <m>t</m>, in seconds, is given by <m>H(t)=-9.4675t^2+615.3846t+24000</m>.
                    <ol label="a.">
                        <li><p>Determine the maximum height of the plane and how long it takes to reach that height.</p></li>

                        <li><p>The zero-gravity effect is experienced near the top of the parabolic path, when the plane is above <m>32{,}520.71</m> feet. For how long do the astronauts experience weightlessness during each cycle?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>The Vertex Form of a Parabola</title>
        <p></p>
        <p>We have learned the standard form of quadratic functions, which is <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m>. In this subsection, we will learn another form called the vertex form.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="02h9yhc7ruc" />
            <video youtube="L8-7QepRSi8" />
        </figure>

        <p>Using graphing technology, we will graph <m>f(x)=x^2-6x+7</m> and <m>g(x)=(x-3)^2-2</m> on the same axes.</p>

            <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)=x^2-6x+7</m> and <m>g(x)=(x-3)^2-2</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-5,ymax=5,xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                        ytick={-4,-2,...,4},
                                        minor ytick={-5,-4,...,5},
                                        xtick={-4,-2,...,4},
                                        minor xtick={-5,-4,...,5},
                                        xlabel={x},ylabel={y}]
                                \addplot [<->, red, domain=0.354:5] {(x-3)^2-2};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(3,-2)} node[below, red] {$(3,-2)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

        <p>We see only one parabola because these are two different forms of the same function. We can see this if we put <m>g(x)</m> in standard form.<md>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=(x-3)^2-2</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=(x-3)(x-3)-2</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=x^2-6x+9-2</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=x^2-6x+7</mrow></md>
            Now it is clear that <m>g(x)</m> and <m>f(x)</m> are the same function.</p>

        <p>The function <m>g(x)</m> is written in vertex form, which is very useful because it allows us to read the vertex without doing any calculations. The vertex of the parabola is <m>(3,-2)</m>. We can see those numbers in <m>g(x)=(x-3)^2-2</m>. The <m>x</m>-value is the solution to <m>(x-3)=0</m>, and the y-value is the constant at the end.</p>

        <p>Here are the graphs of three more functions in vertex form. Compare each function with the vertex of its graph.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="30% 30% 30%" margins="0%">
                <figure xml:id="figure-vertex-in-first-quadrant">
                <caption>The graph of <m>r(x)=(x-2)^2+1</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-0.449:4.449] {(x-2)^2+1};
                                    \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(2,1)} node[right, red] {$(2,1)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure xml:id="figure-vertex-in-second-quadrant">
                <caption>The graph of <m>s(x)=-\frac{1}{4}(x+1)^2+3</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-7:5.325] {-1/4*(x+1)^2+3};
                                    \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-1,3)} node[left, red] {$(-1,3)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure xml:id="figure-vertex-in-third-quadrant">
                <caption>The graph of <m>t(x)=4(x+3)^2-3.5</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-4.62:-1.38] {4*(x+3)^2-3.5};
                                    \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-3,-3.5)} node[below, red] {$(-3,-3.5)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

        <p>Notice that the <m>x</m>-coordinate is the opposite of the value in the function but the <m>y</m>-coordinate has the same sign as the value in the function. Let's look at an example to understand why. We will substitute <m>x=2</m> in the function <m>r(x)</m> from <xref ref="figure-vertex-in-first-quadrant">Figure</xref>.<md>
            <mrow>r(x)\amp=(x-2)^2+1</mrow>
            <mrow>r(\substitute{2})\amp=(\substitute{2}-2)^2+1</mrow>
            <mrow>r(2)\amp=(0)^2+1</mrow>
            <mrow>r(2)\amp=1</mrow></md>
        The <m>x</m>-value is the solution to <m>(x-2)=0</m>, so it is a positive <m>2</m>. When we plug in <m>x=2</m> we get the value <m>y=1</m>, which is the vertex at <m>(2,1)</m>. Now we can define the vertex form of a quadratic function.</p>

        <fact xml:id="fact-vertex-form">
            <title>Vertex Form of a Quadratic Function</title>
            <idx><h>Vertex Form of a Quadratic Function</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>A quadratic function with its vertex at the point <m>(h,k)</m> is given by <m>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <p>Now you can try reading the vertex of each function.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the vertex of each quadratic function.
                <ol label="a.">
                    <li><p><m>r(x)=-2(x+4)^2+10</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>s(t)=5(t-1)^2+10</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>t(x)=(x-10)^2-5</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>u(v)=3(v+7)^2-13</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>r(x)=-2(x+4)^2+10</m> is <m>(-4,10)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>s(t)=5(t-1)^2+2</m> is <m>(1,2)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>t(x)=(x-10)^2-5</m> is <m>(10,-5)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The vertex of <m>u(v)=3(v+7)^2-13</m> is <m>(-7,-13)</m>.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Once we read the vertex from the function, we can also graph the parabola by hand. Here is an example.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the vertex of the parabola <m>p(x)=-(x+2)^2+3</m>, and then sketch the graph.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>For <m>p(x)=-(x+2)^2+3</m>, the vertex is <m>(-2,3)</m>, and it opens downward.</p>

                <p>We need at least one more point to sketch the parabola. An easy point to find is the <m>y</m>-intercept. We will substitute <m>x=0</m> into the function, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>p(x)\amp=-(x+2)^2+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>p(0)\amp=-(0+2)^2+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-4+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-1</mrow>
                </md>The parabola's <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-1)</m> and it's symmetric point is (-4,-1). Now we can sketch its graph:</p>

                <figure>
                    <!-- TODO: Fix coordinate labels -->
                    <caption>Graph of <m>p(x)=-(x+2)^2+3</m></caption>
                    <image width="48%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=5,xmin=-10,xmax=5,
                                        ytick={-9,-7,...,3},
                                        minor ytick={-9,-7,...,3},
                                        xtick={-9,-7,...,3},
                                        minor xtick={-9,-7,...,3},
                                        xlabel={x},ylabel={y}]
                                \addplot [<->, red, domain=-5.606:1.606] {-(x+2)^2+3};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-2,3)} node[above, red] {$(-2,3)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(0,-1)} node[right, red] {$(0,-1)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-4,-1)} node[left, red] {$(-4,-1)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>


